WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.040
I work in cancer research, where I lead a computational team that solves challenges

00:00:10.040 --> 00:00:13.840
in drug development, but that's not what I'm here to talk about.

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:18.219
Like many of you, I'm really excited to be here learning about MLOps and tidy models

00:00:18.219 --> 00:00:20.320
and quarto and all those things.

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:23.600
And I think those are all great skills that help you be good at your job.

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:27.780
However, I want to talk to you about a skill that I think can help you be great at your

00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:30.180
job, and that is creativity.

00:00:30.180 --> 00:00:33.540
And I want to walk you through some of the steps that I took in my creative process for

00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:36.020
using R to help design a quilt.

00:00:36.020 --> 00:00:39.099
And hopefully that will extend a little bit more into how you can apply these things to

00:00:39.099 --> 00:00:44.599
get better enjoyment and fulfillment out of your personal projects but also your day job.

00:00:44.599 --> 00:00:47.419
And so first I have to start with a disclosure slide.

00:00:47.419 --> 00:00:53.500
And my disclosure is that I'm actually not a creative person, or I never thought I was

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:56.759
creative, because creative people look like this.

00:00:56.759 --> 00:01:01.520
They have, like, paint coming out of their chest, they have, like, light bulbs around

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:04.760
their head, and they're genetically more creative.

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:09.000
They have creative parents, and they just know how to solve problems, and ideas come

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.199
to them from heaven.

00:01:11.199 --> 00:01:16.360
And I went to engineering school for almost ten years, and I'm good at math, and I like

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:21.239
it when there's a correct answer, and I can follow steps to get to that correct answer.

00:01:21.239 --> 00:01:26.199
However, I'm in an industry that requires a lot of innovation, and I looked around at

00:01:26.199 --> 00:01:29.199
the people who were doing inspiring work around me.

00:01:29.199 --> 00:01:32.980
And whether those are people that, you know, report to me or are people who are influential

00:01:32.980 --> 00:01:35.639
in the field, they were very creative.

00:01:35.639 --> 00:01:39.940
And so I, you know, as a good professional, I've been on a journey over the last some

00:01:39.940 --> 00:01:45.620
years to learn skills and to practice being more creative and learning techniques to also

00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:49.480
help teams and cultures be more creative.

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:51.779
So now quilting.

00:01:51.779 --> 00:01:54.940
For those of you who don't know what a quilt is, it's a blanket, and quilting has been

00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:57.660
in practice for thousands of years.

00:01:57.660 --> 00:01:59.839
And what makes a quilt is that you have three layers.

00:01:59.839 --> 00:02:04.379
You have a top, you have an insulating middle layer, and you have a back layer.

00:02:04.379 --> 00:02:09.100
And to quilt, you connect these layers together, usually with thread, and this can be very

00:02:09.100 --> 00:02:10.100
decorative.

00:02:10.100 --> 00:02:11.820
It's an art form.

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:17.779
And personally, I got really excited about making quilts as art, and particularly the

00:02:17.779 --> 00:02:19.300
modern quilting movement.

00:02:19.300 --> 00:02:24.300
Oh, before I say that, I just want to put this in our terms that everyone can understand.

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:28.619
Quilting is just fabric, you cut up, you sew together, and then you sew it together

00:02:28.619 --> 00:02:29.619
again.

00:02:29.619 --> 00:02:30.619
Okay.

00:02:30.619 --> 00:02:35.940
So back to modern quilting, this is an example of a beautiful modern quilt.

00:02:35.940 --> 00:02:40.380
It has these organic shapes made out of fabric.

00:02:40.380 --> 00:02:44.220
This one I also love, extremely different, but it has this beautiful composition that

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:47.419
draws your eye around the frame.

00:02:47.419 --> 00:02:51.339
Quilts can also play with color, like this example, which is really challenging to do,

00:02:51.339 --> 00:02:55.779
given that you don't have every color in the rainbow available to you in fabric.

00:02:55.779 --> 00:02:58.220
Quilts can also have political messages.

00:02:58.220 --> 00:03:02.860
Or quilts can be personal, like this is a self-portrait, someone made in fabric.

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:07.179
So I was really excited about this, and that brings me to the prerequisite.

00:03:07.179 --> 00:03:10.300
The prerequisite is that you are excited about your work.

00:03:10.300 --> 00:03:13.580
I don't think you need to be the most experienced person.

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:17.179
So I started quilting at the beginning of 2021.

00:03:17.179 --> 00:03:21.339
I bought a sewing machine a little over a year ago, but I'm not going to let that stop

00:03:21.339 --> 00:03:25.500
me doing something interesting if I'm excited about it.

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:30.539
So the first step in my creative process is to come up with too many ideas.

00:03:30.539 --> 00:03:35.179
I'm somebody that I like to come up with one idea, and then execute the crap out of it.

00:03:35.179 --> 00:03:39.419
Like don't keep thinking about other things, but my new method is that I try to come up

00:03:39.419 --> 00:03:41.259
with more ideas than I think I need.

00:03:41.259 --> 00:03:45.660
I have an idea quota, where I come up with 10 ideas, 40 ideas, 50 ideas.

00:03:45.740 --> 00:03:50.220
From that, you end up with new ideas that you had never originally thought on day one,

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:54.139
and also takes you in directions that lets you better curate your ideas.

00:03:54.779 --> 00:03:59.419
And what I ended up doing with this project was coming up with a solution where I could

00:03:59.419 --> 00:04:00.539
fuse two domains.

00:04:01.419 --> 00:04:06.300
And I had just taken a drawing class, and I learned about the concept of two-point perspective.

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:12.220
Two-point perspective is a way to make a 3D visualization in two dimensions, like these

00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:13.020
cuboid shapes.

00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:17.739
And I also know about R, and I thought, well, I'm really excited about the things that are

00:04:17.739 --> 00:04:20.140
happening with generative art using R.

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:25.260
Could I create some sort of landscape in this way, a 3D, 2D production of a 3D landscape

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:27.739
using R, using something like geom polygon?

00:04:28.459 --> 00:04:32.220
And so with that, I was really happy with that idea, and I started to go forward.

00:04:34.540 --> 00:04:36.619
So step two was I did a lot of improvisation.

00:04:37.179 --> 00:04:40.140
So I can start to learn, how could I make this visualization in R?

00:04:40.700 --> 00:04:43.100
How could I mess around with the dimensions?

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:48.619
How many shapes I wanted, the size of these, the overall aspect ratio of the colors?

00:04:50.779 --> 00:04:57.019
And then I had to do a lot of research, because the fact is that the design that I had chosen

00:04:57.660 --> 00:05:01.980
is not easily convertible to fabric, which is not something that I had planned for.

00:05:02.619 --> 00:05:07.579
So I had to come up with some techniques that would allow me to construct my design in fabric,

00:05:07.579 --> 00:05:11.339
and that is where I want to talk to you a little bit about a technique I really like,

00:05:11.339 --> 00:05:13.579
which is called foundation paper piecing.

00:05:13.579 --> 00:05:15.500
It's a little bit of a rabbit hole, I'll go down with you.

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:21.820
So this is a technique where you create a design, and you print it on a piece of paper.

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:26.540
So you have a design like this, and you actually sequentially sew fabric to that design.

00:05:26.540 --> 00:05:29.899
So this is what the back would look like, and then the front looks like this.

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:34.299
And this is an amazing technique, because it allows you to do very, very

00:05:34.299 --> 00:05:36.940
precise piecing of fabrics together.

00:05:37.019 --> 00:05:39.100
Those lines are all perfectly parallel.

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:41.420
You can have very, very small pieces.

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:45.339
And this lends itself very much to the technique and the design that I wanted to make.

00:05:46.299 --> 00:05:51.739
But there's a problem in that this technique also imparts a new geometrical constraint

00:05:51.739 --> 00:05:53.500
in the type of a design you can create.

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:59.179
So you can only add one piece of fabric at a time, and you can only add one seam at a time,

00:05:59.179 --> 00:06:03.660
which seems simple, but it does impose a constraint on the amount of design that you can do.

00:06:03.739 --> 00:06:08.779
So for something like my design, I'm in trouble, because this is not pieceable.

00:06:08.779 --> 00:06:12.940
This design with this Y junction in the middle, I cannot do, because I would have to add two

00:06:12.940 --> 00:06:14.859
pieces of fabric at the same time.

00:06:14.859 --> 00:06:15.579
It doesn't work.

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:21.339
So the way that people who design these patterns work is it's basically like a Sudoku puzzle.

00:06:21.339 --> 00:06:26.619
It's all done by hand, where you look at this, and I say, well, I can't do this in one block,

00:06:26.619 --> 00:06:31.660
so I'll split it into two, and then I have to design where my seams will go,

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:33.899
and then I also have to determine the correct order,

00:06:33.899 --> 00:06:37.579
because if I don't add these pieces in the correct order, it won't work.

00:06:38.619 --> 00:06:42.140
And I really thought a lot about, okay, well, is there a way I could use R

00:06:42.140 --> 00:06:44.859
or some other, you know, framework to help me do this?

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:48.940
And I found a wonderful paper that was published just last year by Mackenzie Leak

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:54.140
and others at Stanford University, which actually gets into the mathematical foundation for doing

00:06:54.140 --> 00:06:59.019
this, and I really recommend, if you're interested, to go ahead and read this paper.

00:06:59.019 --> 00:07:03.179
They've also got some YouTube videos and even a web app that you can use to help design your

00:07:03.179 --> 00:07:03.739
own designs.

00:07:04.779 --> 00:07:08.619
And so I don't really want to talk about graph theory, although I do a little bit,

00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:14.859
which is that these designs are then represented as hypergraphs, where each piece is a node in

00:07:14.859 --> 00:07:19.899
the graph, and each seam is an edge, and this allows you, then, to determine if your design

00:07:19.899 --> 00:07:24.779
is peaceable and also automatically derive the order that you would add the pieces.

00:07:24.779 --> 00:07:25.420
It's really cool.

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:29.339
So if we take a complicated design, like the one I made of the R logo on the left,

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:34.779
that's actually four pieces, and I can represent them as four graphs, and from that, I can

00:07:34.779 --> 00:07:39.019
determine that my design was good because it was peaceable, and also the order that I need

00:07:39.019 --> 00:07:40.299
to add the pieces.

00:07:40.299 --> 00:07:41.100
So that was great.

00:07:41.739 --> 00:07:42.299
I'm good.

00:07:43.179 --> 00:07:44.779
Except for now I have to make the quilt.

00:07:46.299 --> 00:07:50.459
And execution is a really hard part of creativity, because if you just have a lot of ideas and

00:07:50.459 --> 00:07:54.459
you don't actually follow through and finish them, it's really hard to make the quilt.

00:07:56.059 --> 00:07:56.859
That's a problem.

00:07:57.899 --> 00:08:02.459
So I started to work on my sewing machine, and I worked on it for a while, and one of

00:08:02.459 --> 00:08:07.420
the things that I think is really helpful as part of a creative process is to seek advice

00:08:07.420 --> 00:08:08.220
or collaboration.

00:08:08.779 --> 00:08:11.579
So here I actually went on quilting Reddit.

00:08:11.579 --> 00:08:12.619
Of course, that exists.

00:08:12.619 --> 00:08:16.140
And I posted my quilt and asked, you know, somebody give me some ideas here.

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:17.019
I'm kind of stuck.

00:08:17.019 --> 00:08:18.380
And people were really generous.

00:08:18.380 --> 00:08:22.700
They gave me these schematics back, like, hey, try this, try that, which was fantastic.

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:27.339
Another thing that is part of executing is that you're going to make mistakes.

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:34.299
And the interesting thing about a visual art like quilting is that your mistakes are visceral,

00:08:34.940 --> 00:08:35.979
and they're hard to hide.

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:40.619
So in my Git repo, I can kind of hide my mistakes, although I don't.

00:08:40.619 --> 00:08:43.179
I usually write, like, big mistake, big mess, clean this up.

00:08:43.979 --> 00:08:46.940
But when I have something physical, that mistake is there.

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:50.940
And I think it helps you get better at making mistakes, because you can see them and you

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:51.900
can be like, it's okay.

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:53.260
It's part of growing and learning.

00:08:55.260 --> 00:08:55.820
Okay.

00:08:55.820 --> 00:08:59.739
And so then this is the other part that's really hard, is that you have to share your work.

00:09:00.299 --> 00:09:02.460
So I did bring this quilt with me.

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:04.219
I have to put this mic down.

00:09:08.059 --> 00:09:08.559
Okay.

00:09:10.619 --> 00:09:13.739
So I think here we go.

00:09:22.859 --> 00:09:24.780
Thank you for humoring me.

00:09:24.780 --> 00:09:28.380
But I think this is one of the first Gigi plots ever made in Fabric.

00:09:28.940 --> 00:09:30.859
Probably not the first, but one of the first.

00:09:32.539 --> 00:09:37.979
But there is another step, which is that oftentimes you find that the question you were asking

00:09:37.979 --> 00:09:42.619
when you started is not actually the most important question or the right question that

00:09:42.619 --> 00:09:43.580
you should have been asking.

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:45.580
And that definitely happened here.

00:09:46.380 --> 00:09:50.140
I started off, and I thought, like, yeah, I'll just make a plot, and then I'll make

00:09:50.140 --> 00:09:50.940
it in Fabric.

00:09:50.940 --> 00:09:51.979
That's the right question.

00:09:52.780 --> 00:09:56.619
And I came up with these other ideas, which are really interesting research that I could

00:09:56.619 --> 00:09:58.940
actually be performing as part of this process.

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:02.219
Everything from, like, how do I choose the right colors?

00:10:02.219 --> 00:10:04.380
How do I determine how much fabric to order?

00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:08.619
To how do I try to design these blocks more intelligently?

00:10:09.260 --> 00:10:12.219
So that's one of the future work that I'm working on at the moment.

00:10:12.780 --> 00:10:16.460
For example, the R logo is really hard to make as a quilt.

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:17.659
It has some curved shapes.

00:10:17.659 --> 00:10:19.260
It has some square shapes.

00:10:19.260 --> 00:10:21.820
Really difficult to represent that actually in Fabric.

00:10:22.460 --> 00:10:24.700
So I could do something sort of naive here.

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:29.419
I can create a pixelated design, which I think it's actually pretty cool.

00:10:29.419 --> 00:10:32.140
But it doesn't really look like the R logo to me.

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:33.260
So I wasn't happy with that.

00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:39.179
So then I can do this, which is just I kind of mostly by hand generated this pattern.

00:10:39.179 --> 00:10:40.059
And I think that's great.

00:10:40.059 --> 00:10:41.979
I think it looks just like the R logo.

00:10:41.979 --> 00:10:43.739
So success story.

00:10:43.739 --> 00:10:47.900
Except if I wanted to go a step further and have the code generate this for me,

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:50.619
that's what I'm working on.

00:10:50.619 --> 00:10:54.380
And if you're a close observer, you can see that this doesn't look right.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:57.979
You don't have to humor me.

00:10:57.979 --> 00:10:58.619
It's not right.

00:10:59.979 --> 00:11:02.059
But from this, I am learning a lot.

00:11:02.059 --> 00:11:03.260
There's a process here.

00:11:03.260 --> 00:11:05.020
And I'm learning interesting things.

00:11:05.020 --> 00:11:07.020
And I think it's leading in different directions.

00:11:07.020 --> 00:11:08.299
I can take that kind of thing.

00:11:08.299 --> 00:11:10.619
And I can make a self-portrait of myself.

00:11:10.619 --> 00:11:14.940
I'm working on other approaches where I can have code generate a design,

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:17.260
but as well the fabric choices that you could use.

00:11:18.219 --> 00:11:22.059
So now that I've described the process, I have to be honest with you.

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:24.619
I didn't describe it entirely.

00:11:24.619 --> 00:11:26.140
In that, I kind of made up the order.

00:11:26.859 --> 00:11:30.539
For the purpose of the talk, I thought it would be helpful to say like 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.

00:11:31.419 --> 00:11:34.140
But in reality, that's not the order that I did these things.

00:11:34.140 --> 00:11:35.979
And that's true with a lot of creative work.

00:11:35.979 --> 00:11:38.700
Whether you're doing it for your day job or for your art projects.

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:42.059
Generally, it's a very nonlinear process.

00:11:42.059 --> 00:11:43.900
Which is something that I personally struggle with,

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:46.780
because I would like it to be a linear process with like a right answer.

00:11:48.059 --> 00:11:50.539
But that's something that can help you strengthen your work.

00:11:51.659 --> 00:11:58.059
Okay, so I want to now talk about a couple tortured metaphors

00:11:58.059 --> 00:12:03.500
that I've learned from other people that I think apply to my work in computational research.

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:06.539
And hopefully, also will resonate with some of you

00:12:06.539 --> 00:12:09.340
in the kind of work that you do and how you could try to be more creative.

00:12:10.460 --> 00:12:14.619
So this first example, I learned from a colleague of mine at BMS, Joe Sostakowsky.

00:12:14.619 --> 00:12:19.260
And the question is, would you rather be a pizza deliverer or would you rather be a plumber?

00:12:20.539 --> 00:12:21.419
I'll let people think.

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:24.619
Okay, how do you get pizza?

00:12:24.619 --> 00:12:26.859
I order pizza a lot, and it's great.

00:12:26.859 --> 00:12:30.700
I can get on my phone, I can say what toppings I want, how many pizzas.

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:35.260
And then I get like a photo of the pizza on my doorstep.

00:12:35.260 --> 00:12:36.219
It's incredible, right?

00:12:36.219 --> 00:12:38.380
It works really, really well for food delivery.

00:12:38.940 --> 00:12:42.380
But I've also been on teams where I'm a data analyst.

00:12:42.380 --> 00:12:45.099
And I'm asked for things in the same way.

00:12:45.099 --> 00:12:47.580
Somebody goes on and they order a data pizza.

00:12:47.580 --> 00:12:50.780
They say, I need this dashboard with these features with this data.

00:12:51.419 --> 00:12:54.299
And I don't think that's a very effective way to do data work.

00:12:54.299 --> 00:12:57.179
I don't think that's a good way for you to get insights from data.

00:12:58.619 --> 00:13:00.700
And it doesn't leave any room for creativity

00:13:00.700 --> 00:13:04.140
or trying to get to what are really the right questions you should be asking.

00:13:04.140 --> 00:13:07.340
So a slight iteration on that is to think about a plumber.

00:13:07.340 --> 00:13:10.059
So a plumber is a subject matter expert, right?

00:13:10.059 --> 00:13:13.580
I have a plumber come to my house, and they talk to me about what my problems are.

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:15.820
They bring their own toolkit.

00:13:15.820 --> 00:13:17.340
They have their own expertise.

00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:19.739
And they try to understand really what my needs are.

00:13:19.739 --> 00:13:22.299
And they work on a solution that will meet my needs.

00:13:23.419 --> 00:13:26.140
OK, so if you don't like that one, that's fine.

00:13:26.140 --> 00:13:26.859
I have another one.

00:13:28.380 --> 00:13:31.500
So this one is, would you rather be a detective or a criminal?

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:34.539
And it's a trick question.

00:13:34.539 --> 00:13:35.580
You actually want to be both.

00:13:36.219 --> 00:13:40.460
So this is actually one from Albert Einstein.

00:13:40.460 --> 00:13:43.340
And so this is about explaining why science is so difficult.

00:13:43.979 --> 00:13:46.460
So if you take a detective, like a Sherlock Holmes,

00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:48.700
there's a murder's been committed.

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:50.859
And you collect clues, and you have hypotheses.

00:13:50.859 --> 00:13:52.460
Like, it's a jealous girlfriend.

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:54.940
It's a ex-colleague or whatever.

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:56.619
And you put together all these clues.

00:13:56.619 --> 00:14:00.460
And then you discover, like, oh, actually, it was a poisonous jellyfish that killed the person.

00:14:00.460 --> 00:14:02.539
Like, that's how a detective works, right?

00:14:03.099 --> 00:14:06.299
But the key is that a detective knows what crime they're solving.

00:14:06.299 --> 00:14:08.380
The problem is really well-defined.

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:09.580
This person's been murdered.

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:10.539
This has been stolen.

00:14:11.099 --> 00:14:11.979
I know how to solve it.

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:16.780
But the difference is, for a scientist, you have to also come up with the questions.

00:14:17.820 --> 00:14:20.299
So in that way, you have to commit the crime.

00:14:20.299 --> 00:14:22.299
And you have to perform the investigation.

00:14:23.020 --> 00:14:25.900
And I find this is a really apt metaphor for the work that I do.

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:30.539
Because you have to constantly be asking, am I asking the right questions?

00:14:30.539 --> 00:14:33.979
Is this the important line of research that I should be following?

00:14:33.979 --> 00:14:37.260
And I think that's a really, really important part of doing science

00:14:37.820 --> 00:14:39.739
that requires you to be creative.

00:14:41.260 --> 00:14:41.979
OK.

00:14:41.979 --> 00:14:46.140
So to wrap those thoughts up, I would say you should be a plumber.

00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:48.780
You should also commit science crimes.

00:14:50.059 --> 00:14:53.340
And I would also encourage you to think about celebrating your mistakes

00:14:53.340 --> 00:14:55.580
and also getting exposure to new ideas.

00:14:55.580 --> 00:14:59.659
So I think at meetings like this, it's great to go to talks that you might not think

00:14:59.659 --> 00:15:00.539
would be interesting.

00:15:01.099 --> 00:15:05.099
I would also encourage you to find your local, like, our user group, our ladies group,

00:15:05.099 --> 00:15:08.140
or our meetup group to try to attend talks and meet people

00:15:08.140 --> 00:15:10.859
that you might not normally meet in your day job.

00:15:11.820 --> 00:15:12.320
OK.

00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:15.500
With that, I have some acknowledgments or resources

00:15:15.500 --> 00:15:18.539
if you're interested in learning more about creativity.

00:15:18.539 --> 00:15:21.020
And this is also a work in progress that I have.

00:15:21.020 --> 00:15:23.659
And you might recognize that that is Geome Point.

00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:25.340
All right.

00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:25.840
Thank you.

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:26.900
Thank you.

